Core funding provided to regional and global networks that address HIV and human rights needs of ISPs (at national, regional and global level)
1a. Institutionally stronger ISP and civil society networks and consortia
1b. Improved and sustainable advocacy capcity for ISP and civil society networks and consortia
2. Increased influence of ISP and civil society networks and consortia to make changes with regards to HIV and human right issues
3a. More enabling rights-affirming social, policy and legal environment for ISPs
3b. More accessible, right-based, quality HIV services and programs for ISPs
3c. Resources made available and spent properly to create better conditions for ISPs with regards to HIV and human rights
Impact: Better health, inclusion and social wellbeing for ISPs

ISPs refer to people living with HIV, people who use drugs (PWUD), sex workers (SW), the Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender and Transsexual, Intersex, Queer (LGBTIQ+) communities which includes men who have sex with men (MSM), women and girls, vulnerable youth, migrants, people living in rural areas and prisoners.

PITCH seeks to strengthen the capacities of local civil society organisations to advocate for sexual and reproductive health and rights, and uphold the human rights of key populations. Our work centres around key populations, adolescent girls and young women in nine countries in East, West and Southern Africa, South-East Asia, and Central Europe. These communities in many contexts carry the main HIV burden. At the same time, they are often neglected in the HIV response and face many barriers in accessing HIV and SRH services as well as human rights violations. PITCH addresses this urgent gap, and is reactive and responsive to local needs/urgencies that have been identified in its geographical foci.

Partners under the Bridging the Gaps programme aim to end AIDS among key populations. If civil society is strengthened, if fulfilment of human rights for key populations is increased and if sexual and reproductive health is improved and HIV transmission reduced, governments will be hold to account and AIDS among key populations can end.

Globally, sex workers are disproportionately impacted by HIV , and face heightened risks of STI transmission. Sex workers are twelve times more likely to be living with HIV than the general population. Sex workers have been recognised as a key population for HIV programming given the disproportionate burden of HIV carried by female, male and transgender sex workers and their increased vulnerability and lack of access to SRHR services as a result of criminalisation, violence, discrimination and stigma.

Human rights violation cases acted on is the number of violations documented and in the process of being acted on, instead of responded to, meaning that the cases are taken further than documentation, for example  reporting, providing psychosocial and or paralegal or legal support.
Law enforcement staff trained on human rights is measured by the number of law enforcement staff trained on human rights.

Service provision to key population members measures the number of services used by key population members. This is done through 6 indicators that respectively measure the number of testing services, treatment services, PWUD specific medical harm reduction services, other health services meaning condom distribution, social services and legal support services used by key population members.

Participation of partner organization in or organization of local national regional or global stakeholder meetings is measured by the number of partner organisations that participate in meetings. Meetings are defined as advocacy meetings with local national regional or global stakeholders.
Number of Global level advocacy tools campaigns and resources developed

Trained service providers is measured through 2 indicators. The first measures the number of service providers trained. Service providers provide social services, including psychosocial support, health education and promotion, online counselling, or health NGO or public sector services. The counselling part of VCT services is excluded. They are individuals within local partner organisations within BtG that provide services, as well as from indirect service providers that receive training from BtG local partners for instance  other NGO-run clinics, private clinics, state-run services, etc. The second measures the number of legal service providers trained including paralegal services
